 how the khans and their families built more than they tore down. She demonstrates that the stipulations of the Chinese building system were powerful and resilient enough to guide the architecture that rose under Mongolian rule.Drawing on Steinhardt’s groundbreaking textual research in numerous languages as well as her pioneering fieldwork at sites across East Asia, Yuan will become the standard reference on this critical period of cultural and artistic exchange.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitecturezChinaxHistoryySong-Yuan dynasties, 960-1368. 0aArchitecture, ChineseySong-Yuan dynasties, 960-1368. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  aConfucian temple.  aMongolia and eastern Russia.  aMongolian.  aMuslim Burial.  aShangdu.  aSpaces of the Empire.  aTemple to Mani.  aTibetan Pagodas.  aTugh Temur.  aarchitecture of death.  aarzhai.  abrick.  achina monasteries for muslim prayer.  acloud terrace at juyong pass.  adaidu.  aeast Asian archaeologists.  aeast of china.  afeilaifeng.  agansu.  aguangsheng monastery.  ahalls to the gods.  ajapan’s buddhist monasteries.  alongshan.  ametal.  amongol century.  amongol patrons.  anorth china.  aobservatory in dengfeng.  arock-carved architecture.  asouth of Mongolia.  asoutheastern china.  asouthwestern china.  astone.  athree pavilions.  atranquility hall.  atwo towers.  avisons of empire.  awalled enclosures.  ayonglegong.  ayuan buildings.  ayuan wooden halls.  ayuan-period.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691253350?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691253350423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691253350/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles